use associations to link to the daemon/port metrics instead.

for example, https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/a1347418307d31a94bd21f22897aa508df938dcf/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Inventory/Item/PCIeDevice.interface.yaml#L303-L311
Done
size?
Done
this should be `xyz.openbmc_project.Metric.Port`?
Ack
maybe prefer lowercase?
Would it be fine to have only that lowercase? Port is Upper case
maybe all of them as lowercase.
Open to discussion
this should be `xyz.openbmc_project.Metric.Daemon`?
Ack
these are percentage, right? maybe need to mention it.
Done
does uptime needs to be double?
Yes I believe so. We could theoretically truncate off the seconds, but I think double makes sense as it would be a floating point number
Ack
double makes more sense as it would allow more precision in our metric*

No.  Please follow the conventions by EpochTime and elsewhere when it comes to time.

uint64 of microseconds.

What do you mean by this? Usually EpochTime is used to determine a timestamp. The number of milliseconds since the last epoch is used to determine what point in time something occurred. It is not used for ranges of times such as how long a program or system has been active.

If you mean make the uptime (how long the bmc has been booted up) in uint64 of milliseconds/microseconds passed from current time since boot, then I will make the change.

Also I found Entry.interface.yaml in the Logging folder and it seems to use milliseconds and not microseconds, which is the convention?

>> If you mean make the uptime (how long the bmc has been booted up) in uint64 of milliseconds/microseconds passed from current time since boot, then I will make the change.

Edward from Patrick's comment i can deduce he meant what u mentioned above. Probably, he can correct us.

Patrick, i also see time in milliseconds rather than microseconds, for example at https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/State/Watchdog.interface.yaml#L41. Can you please confirm if its fine to use milliseconds?

We've been trying to refactor all the time intervals to be in usec.  That's why I referenced EpochTime as the canonical reference on how to do time.

There are quite likely existing interfaces that are using a different time unit, but that is just because they're older and not yet refactored.
So it is currentTime - bootTime in microseconds?
use a enum instead of arbitrary string
Done

In priority order, my concerns with this:
1. each metric should be timestamped, typically with the time the metric was sampled
2. support for reading multiple timestamped values of a single metric, so sampling time isn't necessarily the same as when client tries to read.  I'm expecting client to be something that wants to export metrics off the BMC.  instead of polling at the sampling frequency it can have a lower collection frequency.
3. metrics are read one at a time? Maybe there's a bulk property read in the that might make this better.

One more thought, though this is more work.
A more generic interface that exports metrics of different types.  If you look at metric systems like OpenTelemetry, OpenCensus, Prometheus, they all define metric types like gauge, historgram, counts.  Each metric is named. Versus each metric being explicitly being written out in the yaml.

Something like this might make it easy for individual daemons to add their own custom metrics too, without having to add to this interface explicitly.  It's a use case we have but I'm not sure about OpenBMC in general.

I'm question is dbus is the right level for this abstraction or if that's better left to an exporter.
erase #3.  dbus has a GetAll and that would work.
size is potentially problematic here if you're planning to track bytes, right?
Memory allocation is listed based on page sizes and a page is a whole number of bytes. Could you clarify more on what you mean by problematic?

Edward,
My understanding is you are trying to specify the memory utilization for the BMC which the redfish spec also specifies in just bytes https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/static/redfish/v1/JsonSchemas/ManagerDiagnosticData/ManagerDiagnosticData.json#L400. Also, i see /proc/meminfo shows memory just in kB. So, i can see what Patrick is saying is that size_t might be small for that and its better to use integer instead.

`size` can only hold up to 4GB on 32-bit platforms.  This might or might not be sufficient here.  I'd generally prefer `size` as long as we can rationalize that it'll be fine and we don't need an explicit `uint64`.
I see what you mean now. I havent seen a number that big so far, but uint64 might be the better choice.
How do you plan to obtain these metrics?

My plan is to query the State Manager and store this information on persistent storage. A program will check the lastRebootTime and check whether it is different than what is stored on the persistent data. If so, then it increments the boot count and if the lastRebootReason is Unknown, it increments the crash counter.
Follow time conventions used elsewhere please.
Same as above conversation. If milliseconds or microseconds is what should be used. Then I will make the change.
We usually avoid putting units on property names.
Will do. I just thought it was supposed to be the same as in the schema.
Please follow conventions from yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Network/EthernetInterface.interface.yaml
Ack
Please follow the conventions in EthernetInterface.  Don't encode two binaries as an enumeration.
Done

Edward, Thanks for posting this review. I am in Meta openBMC team and was starting some work on BMC Health Monitoring from Meta side, when Patrick pointed me to this change-set. Since, you have already started work on this, was wondering if you want to collaborate on the effort? Also, added some comments on the change-set. Thanks

I'd prefer if we split this out into 3 commits.  We might want to split the BMC ones into multiple interfaces.  We need to decide if phosphor-health-manager is the right place to hold all of these.  We might want to put BMC memory, BMC cpu, etc. in separate interfaces.  I could see the reboot/crash count being more appropriate to be held by phosphor-debug-collector, in which case it has to be in a separate interface.
Currently we have one daemon containing all of this. I can push this for now and we can refactor it as needed? I am not currently working on the monitoring anymore but I can push the code I have.
We can discuss in our meeting session and we can do some collaboration on this work item.

The redfish schema has more granular memory representation in terms of available, shmem, cached etc https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/static/redfish/v1/JsonSchemas/ManagerDiagnosticData/ManagerDiagnosticData.json#L349. Do we need to further break this up?
Would this not be usecase dependent? Breaking up is fine with me as well.

Since, client interface (redfish) needs that granularity in terms of memory metric, some place we would need to host that and since this sdbus interface is exposing this metric so my suggestion is its better to make it granular by adding more memory subitems.

BMCWeb is already getting the Uptime via ActiveEnterTimestampMonotonic property from systemd https://grok.openbmc.org/xref/openbmc/bmcweb/redfish-core/lib/manager_diagnostic_data.hpp?r=ac106bf6#61, so i suppose we can skip that from this sdbus interface?

Shouldn't this be an association between the BMC metric object and BMC inventory object just as we have currently between sensor (utilization) object and BMC inventory object?
https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Sensor/Value.interface.yaml#L100

Also, would it be better to define Daemon and Port specific associations with BMC inventory in their interface files?
I see what you mean. Would combining the Metric and Inventory object be better instead?
Patrick suggested to keep the interfaces as granular as possible. Since, in this case inventory and metric would be hosted by 2 different daemons, so lets keep them separate.

My understanding is you are trying to map this to "UserTimeSeconds" in https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/static/redfish/v1/JsonSchemas/ManagerDiagnosticData/ManagerDiagnosticData.json#L508.
This will again follow same semantics for type i.e. uint64 in milliseconds?
Yes the conversion can be done in bmcweb
Same as above for type. Use uint64 in milliseconds?
yes
Since its bytes, better to use integer?
yes

Do we need a new sdbus interface for this? We already have an sdbus interface defined for an EthernetInterface in https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Network/EthernetInterface.interface.yaml

Wouldn't it be better to extend the existing interface with new properties?
Since Redfish has different schemas for Port and EthernetInterface I have switched them. I personally dont think we should combine them for that reason.
